# Documentation Best Practices

## General Documentation Principles

- Write clear, concise, and accurate documentation
- Keep documentation up to date with code changes
- Use examples to illustrate concepts
- Write for your audience (beginners vs. experts)
- Document "why" not just "what"
- Keep documentation organized and easy to navigate

## README.md Guidelines

### Essential Sections
- Project title and description
- Features list
- Installation/setup instructions
- Usage examples
- Technologies used
- File structure
- Contributing guidelines (if open source)
- License information

### Best Practices
- Start with a clear project description
- Include screenshots or demos if applicable
- Provide clear setup instructions
- Include code examples
- Keep it updated as the project evolves
- Use proper markdown formatting
- Add a table of contents for long READMEs

## Code Documentation

### Comments
- Write self-documenting code (prefer clear code over comments)
- Add comments for complex logic or algorithms
- Explain "why" not "what"
- Keep comments up to date with code changes
- Remove commented-out code before committing

### JSDoc for JavaScript
- Document function parameters and return values
- Include examples for complex functions
- Document exceptions that may be thrown
- Use proper JSDoc syntax

Example:
```javascript
/**
 * Draws text on canvas with rotation and multi-line support
 * @param {CanvasRenderingContext2D} ctx - The canvas context
 * @param {string} text - The text to draw
 * @param {number} x - X coordinate
 * @param {number} y - Y coordinate
 * @param {string} color - Text color (hex format)
 * @param {number} rotation - Rotation angle in degrees
 */
function drawText(ctx, text, x, y, color, rotation) {
    // ...
}
```

## Inline Documentation

- Use meaningful variable names (self-documenting)
- Break complex operations into named steps
- Add comments for non-obvious code
- Document edge cases and assumptions
- Explain workarounds or temporary solutions

## Git Commit Messages

- Use present tense: "Add feature" not "Added feature"
- Be specific and descriptive
- Reference issues/tickets if applicable
- Keep first line under 50 characters
- Add detailed body for complex changes

Good examples:
- "Fix text positioning bug on canvas resize"
- "Add error handling for image upload failures"
- "Improve accessibility: add ARIA labels to inputs"

Bad examples:
- "fix bug"
- "update code"
- "changes"

## Project Documentation Structure

```
project/
├── README.md              # Main project documentation
├── CHANGELOG.md           # Version history (optional)
├── CONTRIBUTING.md        # Contribution guidelines (optional)
├── LICENSE                # License file
└── docs/                  # Additional documentation (if needed)
    ├── api.md
    └── architecture.md
```

## Documentation Maintenance

- Review documentation when code changes
- Remove outdated information
- Update examples to match current code
- Keep documentation in sync with features
- Ask for feedback on documentation clarity

